# AGENTS.md

## Base Project Instructions

- Preserve any project-specific guidance already present in this repository.
- This project must be a git repository. Run `git init` at the project root when `.git/` is missing, but do not commit, push, or configure remotes unless explicitly requested.
- Load and follow stack-specific skills when they apply to the project.
- Prefer the existing framework, architecture, package manager, formatter, and test runner already present in the repository.
- Keep platform-specific or environment-specific files isolated according to the project structure.
- Add new external services, platform capabilities, permissions, or deployment privileges only when a requirement explicitly needs them.
- For Xcode projects, also load `xcode-project-creator`; use `xcode-terminal` and `xcsift` for Xcode build, test, archive, simulator, and diagnostic work.

## Technical Requirements

- Maintain at least 80% app source code coverage with unit tests.
- Include UI regression tests for UI changes and new screens; prefer screenshot tests when the stack supports them.
- Validate code changes with unit tests before marking tasks finished.
- Validate UI changes with screenshot or equivalent UI regression tests before marking tasks finished.
- Keep reusable build, test, packaging, validation, data-preparation, and release commands under root `scripts/`.
- Create `scripts/` when it is missing.
- Group frequently used scripts by category, such as `scripts/build/`, `scripts/test/`, `scripts/data/`, or project-specific categories.
- Shared auxiliary files for data, configuration, fixtures, or common script settings are allowed and preferred when they prevent duplication.
- Always prefer simple reusable scripts over long one-off shell commands. Common build, test, validation, data-preparation, packaging, release, and snapshot workflows should have stable public scripts with the fewest arguments possible, ideally no arguments.
- When a command needs environment variables, many flags, file-specific paths, redirection, pipes, or formatted output, put those details inside a script instead of asking agents to execute the raw command.
- Prefer public no-argument wrappers backed by private helper scripts when several workflows share project, scheme, destination, derived data, result bundle, output directory, or formatter settings.
- Scripts that produce results should write to stable, ignored output paths such as `.build-results/<workflow>/...` so agents can inspect results later without unique filenames or extra permissions.
- Record frequently used manual commands, script purposes, required environment, and notable patterns in `scripts/used_scripts.md`.
- Treat `scripts/used_scripts.md` as local developer and AI-agent memory, not project history; keep it untracked and prefer `.git/info/exclude` over `.gitignore`.

## Task System

- Discover the active local task checklist before editing task status: prefer an explicit user path, then existing `tasks/tasks.md`, then existing `specifications/tasks.md`. Do not create or restore a `tasks.md` file unless the user explicitly wants a local checklist.
- Preserve an existing task checklist location; do not move or duplicate it just to match the default path.
- Keep all `tasks.md` checklist files ignored by Git. No `tasks.md` file should be tracked in the repository.
- Every checklist item must use Markdown checkbox syntax.
- Finished items must use `- [x]`.
- In-progress items must put `[WIP]` immediately before the task title: `- [ ] [WIP] Task title`.
- Before starting implementation from a checklist task, mark the matching line as WIP by changing `- [ ] Task title` to `- [ ] [WIP] Task title`.
- Place `[WIP]` immediately after the unchecked marker and before the title. Do not append `[WIP]` at the end of the title.
- When selecting the next checklist task, prefer plain unchecked items first. If none remain, resume the smallest matching `- [ ] [WIP]` item instead of treating the checklist as complete.
- When no plain unchecked tasks and no active `[WIP]` tasks remain, write `Status: no task available. Last checked: <YYYY-MM-DD>.` near the top of the active task checklist.
- Before scanning a large checklist, check for `Status: no task available` near the top of the active task checklist; if present, skip the full scan unless the file changed after that status was written or the user explicitly requests a rescan.
- When adding or starting a new task, remove the `Status: no task available` line before marking the task `[WIP]`.
- If the current work is material and no matching unchecked item exists, create a checklist item in the active task checklist already marked as `- [ ] [WIP] Task title`.
- On completion, remove `[WIP]` and mark the line as `- [x] Task title`; if the project requires commits before closing tasks, close the item only after the commit succeeds.
- Pending, blocked, and archived open items must remain unchecked.
- Every task must also have a detail file under one lifecycle folder:
  - `tasks/pending/`
  - `tasks/wip/`
  - `tasks/blocked/`
  - `tasks/finished/`
  - `tasks/archived/`
- New tasks start in `tasks/pending/`.
- Every task detail file must include an `id` header.
- Prefer a random UUID for new task ids when that is the cheapest practical option.
- Name task detail files `<task-id>-<slug>.md`.
- Every task must be categorized as exactly one of `bug` or `feature`.
- Record that category in the task detail header with a `category` field.
- Each detail file header must include `id`, `title`, `status`, `category`, `creation date`, `last update`, and `labels`.
- Move task detail files to `tasks/wip/` when work starts.
- Move task detail files to `tasks/finished/` when closed.
- Move blocked tasks to `tasks/blocked/` and add `blocked by: <task id>` to the task header.
- Move unnecessary tasks to `tasks/archived/` and add `archived on: <date>` to the task header.
- When moving a task, update both the lifecycle folder and the `status` header while preserving task history and acceptance criteria.

## Task Auxiliary Assets

- Use `tasks/aux_assets/` for temporary task-specific image and sound assets, including screenshots, visual bug reports, drafts, reference images, audio captures, sound effects, voice notes, and reference sounds needed to start, review, or fix a task.
- Create `tasks/aux_assets/` when an attached task image or sound asset is needed and the folder does not exist.
- Keep `tasks/aux_assets/` ignored by Git with `tasks/aux_assets/` in `.gitignore`; add the entry when it is missing or the folder is otherwise not ignored.
- Store each attached task asset under `tasks/aux_assets/`.
- Name each asset with the related task id, an incrementing number, and optionally a short meaning: `<task-id>-<number>[-<meaning>].<extension>`.
- Prefer lowercase, hyphenated or underscored meanings, for example `12345-1-new_detail_screen_draft.png` or `12345-2-error_chime.wav`.
- When work starts on a task, inspect `tasks/aux_assets/` for files that begin with that task id and use the relevant assets as task context.
- When the task completes, remove all `tasks/aux_assets/<task-id>-*` files for that task before marking the task finished.
- Do not store durable product assets, source media, generated app assets, or files that should ship with the product in `tasks/aux_assets/`; move those into the appropriate project asset directory and track them normally.

## Specifications

- Use `specifications/` as the project requirements folder.
- Do not use `specs/` for project requirements when following this workflow.
- Always keep a Product Requirements Document at `specifications/prd.md`.
- Preserve existing PRD content; do not overwrite it with a template unless explicitly requested.
- Put new specification files under a dedicated umbrella folder inside `specifications/`, such as `specifications/assets/main_screen_assets.md`.
- Group similar specifications under the same folder, and fuse closely related files when one shorter file is easier for agents to read.
- Keep each specification file under 300 lines; simplify wording or split by topic when needed to preserve that limit.
- Keep PRDs, ADRs, technical specifications, product requirements, architecture notes, and grouped requirement documents under `specifications/`.
- Keep task lifecycle detail files under root `tasks/` for new projects. Preserve existing checklist locations, including `specifications/tasks.md`, when maintaining established projects.

## Roles

### Product Designer

- Operate in plan mode.
- Write and refine product requirements.
- Challenge product decisions that are underspecified, contradictory, risky, or misaligned with user goals.
- Point to issues and ask for more detail when requirements are ambiguous.
- Do not write production code.

### Developer

- Write the code.
- Challenge only technical decisions, implementation risks, architecture risks, or validation gaps.
- Validate code with unit tests.
- Preserve the task lifecycle and update task status as work moves from pending to wip to finished.

### QA Engineer

- Validate the code against product and technical requirements.
- Act as a safeguard for mistakes made by the Developer role.
- Help find and fix bugs.
- Never challenge product decisions or technical decisions.
- Focus on making the system work with the supplied requirements.

### Scout

- Use internet research when current external data, references, examples, libraries, or assets are needed.
- Download data, references, and assets only when licensing, provenance, and project approval are clear.
- Record source URLs and usage constraints near the downloaded artifacts or in the relevant specification.
